      The word Core describes the basic concept of something, and here, the phrase 'Core Java' defines the basic Java that covers the basic concept of Java programming language. We all are aware that Java is one of the well-known and widely used programming languages, and to begin with it, the beginner has to start the journey with Core Java and then towards the Advance Java. The Java programming language is a general-purpose programming language that is based on the OOPs concept. The ocean of Java is too deep to learn, i.e., as much you learn more, you will know its depth. Java is a platform-independent and robust programming language. The principle followed by Java is WORA that says Write Once, Run Anywhere. The programming language is quite simple and easy to understand. But one should know that Core Java is not different from Java. Java is complete in itself, but for the beginners, it is natural that the beginner must begin with the core concepts of Java. In actual, Java has different editions, where Core Java is one of the parts of an edition.

Selenium supports automation across different browsers, platforms and programming languages. Selenium is one of the most widely used open source Web UI (User Interface) automation testing suite.It was originally developed by Jason Huggins in 2004 as an internal tool at Thought Works. Selenium supports automation across different browsers, platforms and programming languages.
      SeleniumSelenium can be used to automate functional tests and can be integrated with automation test tools such as Maven, Jenkins, & Docker to achieve continuous testing. It can also be integrated with tools such as TestNG, & JUnit for managing test cases and generating reports.

      Manual testing is a software testing process in which test cases are executed manually without using any automated tool. All test cases executed by the tester manually according to the end user's perspective. It ensures whether the application is working, as mentioned in the requirement document or not. Test cases are planned and implemented to complete almost 100 percent of the software application. Test case reports are also generated manually. Manual Testing is one of the most fundamental testing processes as it can find both visible and hidden defects of the software. The difference between expected output and output, given by the software, is defined as a defect. The developer fixed the defects and handed it to the tester for retesting.
      Manual testing is mandatory for every newly developed software before automated testing. This testing requires great efforts and time, but it gives the surety of bug-free software. Manual Testing requires knowledge of manual testing techniques but not of any automated testing tool. Manual testing is essential because one of the software testing fundamentals is "100% automation is not possible."

      Framework testing is a type of software testing that focuses on the testing of the underlying software framework that supports the development and implementation of software applications. A software framework is a set of libraries, tools, and best practices that provide a foundation for building applications. Framework testing involves evaluating the framework's features, functions, and capabilities, as well as its compatibility with different platforms, operating systems, and devices. The testing process typically includes functional testing, performance testing, compatibility testing, and security testing.
      Functional testing involves testing the individual components of the framework, such as libraries and modules, to ensure that they perform as expected and meet the functional requirements. Performance testing involves evaluating the framework's performance under different conditions, such as high loads and concurrent users. Compatibility testing involves testing the framework's compatibility with different platforms, operating systems, and devices. Security testing involves evaluating the framework's security features and identifying potential vulnerabilities. The goal of framework testing is to ensure that the framework is reliable, stable, and secure, and that it provides a solid foundation for building high-quality software applications. By testing the framework thoroughly, software developers can be confident that their applications will perform well and meet the needs of their users.

      SQL (Structured Query Language) is a programming language used for managing and manipulating relational databases. It is used to insert, update, delete, and query data stored in a relational database management system (RDBMS). SQL can be used to retrieve data from one or more tables, filter, sort and aggregate data, and join data from multiple tables. SQL is a declarative language, which means that users write SQL statements to specify the desired outcome, and the database management system takes care of the details of how to achieve that outcome.
      SQL syntax includes keywords such as SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, CREATE, and DROP, as well as operators such as LIKE, BETWEEN, and IN. Some popular relational database management systems that use SQL include Oracle, MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server, and PostgreSQL. SQL is an essential tool for working with databases and is widely used in various industries, including finance, healthcare, and e-commerce.

      APIs can be divided into different categories based on their purpose, such as web APIs, operating system APIs, and database APIs. They can also be classified as open or closed, depending on whether they are publicly available or restricted to a particular group of users. APIs are essential in modern software development and play a crucial role in enabling software to be integrated, modular, and scalable. They are also critical in driving innovation and enabling developers to create new and innovative applications by combining different APIs.
